On 2/16 I landed at Mumbai Airport from Goa and found out I had misplaced his passport! The entire team at the Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts - Mumbai showed me great kindness, found my passport and got it back to me. 

Keith Rajan, Hotel Manager Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts Mumbai⁩ & Fagun Singh, Chef Concierge Four Seasons Hotel Mumbai, and Ena Roy - Director of Rooms Four Season Hotel Mumbai helped to get me situated in my room and check again for my passport. 

With no luck, Fagun quickly got to work - pulling a few strings using the power of his Golden Keys - Les Clefs d'Or® International Network he managed to get key contacts with the CISF Authorities from Goa and Mumbai Airport also Air India Lost & Found department in Goa and Mumbai Airport - Dipen Rawat was very helpful from Goa.

After a few hours Fagun got a call confirming that the passport was found at the Goa Airport.

My passport was dispatched by Air India flight 644 departure from Goa at 15:25 hours & landed at Mumbai Airport at 16:50 hours.

Fagun personally headed to the Mumbai Airport and collected the passport - A big thank you to Air India Limited team for all possible support and Rohan Kamble Air India staff for handing over the passport to Fagun at Mumbai International Airport.

I have travelled to 102 countries, but this one visit is going to be unforgettable!

Last December, I lost one of my dearest friends, Frances Hesselbein.

Many might know her as the former CEO of the Girl Scouts of USA, as a leader across different other organizations, or as a recipient of the Presidential Medal of Freedom.

But to me, she wasn’t only a colleague – she was a good friend for over forty years, too.

Frances was the type of person to joke, “Hey, ask me what my blood type is.”

And when you would ask, she’d answer, “It’s B positive!”

She was always overflowing with kindness and warmth – something the people she loved came to know very well.

I’ll never forget the last time I met with her:

During her final days, I paid a visit to her home in Pennsylvania. She was in a near-comatose state… and it was very clear that she was nearing the end of her life.

For the next 20 minutes - our last 20 minutes together - she asked me how I was. She spoke to my wife and continued to ask about my work.

And I realized that this was what made her a great human being – what made her truly one of a kind, the only Frances Hesselbein out there:

Her life, up until the final moments, was spent in service of others. No self-pity. She made our last moments together about me, not her. Even if she was dying.

And I look back at her with gratitude – a person whose heart truly amazed me, and stayed true to her kind, compassionate self up until the end.

Remembering Frances today, as well as all of the people who have played their part in lighting my path.

"The song is ended, but the melody lingers on." - Irving Berlin
